    + 'The basin preserves at least five distinct geological units within its floor and walls, each recording a different chapter of Martian environmental history. Concentric ring structures mark successive zones of impact damage, while the floor contains layered deposits interpreted as lacustrine sediments — remnants of a lake or lakes that may have filled the basin during warmer epochs. A channel system on the southern rim appears to connect Argyre to the Hellas basin and potentially to a wider southern ocean, suggesting that Argyre may have been a node in a global hydrological network.\n\n'
