    + 'Within days of landing on January 25, 2004, Opportunity found exposed bedrock layered with hematite concretions the team nicknamed "blueberries" — BB-sized mineral spheres that formed as groundwater percolated through sedimentary rock. Cross-bedded sandstone in the crater walls showed the distinctive ripple patterns of shallow flowing water. The case for ancient water at Meridiani was essentially closed within weeks. Over the following years, Opportunity went on to discover the first meteorite ever identified on another planet and clay minerals indicating near-neutral-pH water at Endeavour Crater\'s rim.\n\n'
