    description:
      'Amazonis Planitia is one of the smoothest, flattest, and youngest surfaces on Mars — a vast volcanic plain west of Olympus Mons that stretches roughly 2,800 km across the planet\'s northern lowlands. Its remarkably low crater density indicates a surface age of only a few hundred million years, making it one of the most recently resurfaced regions on the planet. In places, the terrain is so featureless that it approaches the theoretical limit of what planetary scientists can measure as "flat."\n\n'
    + 'The plain\'s extreme youth and smoothness are attributed to extensive lava flooding from the Tharsis and Olympus Mons volcanic systems. Enormous sheet flows spread across the lowlands, burying older terrain under meters to tens of meters of fresh basalt. Some flow fronts are so well-preserved that individual lobe boundaries and pressure ridges remain visible in orbital imagery, offering a textbook example of large-scale effusive volcanism in a low-gravity environment where lava can travel much farther than on Earth before solidifying.\n\n'
